<!--
  Chapter 1 — What Is an Argument?
  Section 1.1 ported from book/drafts/ch01-sec01-language.md (rev. 2).
  Sections 1.2 onward remain placeholders.
-->
<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="ch-what-is-an-argument">

  <title>What Is an Argument?</title>

  <introduction xml:id="ch-arguments-intro">
    <p>
      Spend ten minutes listening in any public space and you will see people
      doing all sorts of things with language. They are telling stories,
      ordering food, complaining about traffic, complimenting each other's
      shoes, explaining how the parking app works, confessing crushes, lying
      about their weekends, asking for directions, and, even, on occasion,
      trying to convince someone of something using actual reasons.
    </p>
    <p>
      That last activity, the giving-reasons one, is what we'll call
      <term>making an argument</term>, and it is the subject of this book.
      The other activities are largely where we find and make meaning with
      each other, but arguments are special in their own way as well.
      Arguments let us ask: <em>is this any good?</em> You can't ask that of
      <q>good morning</q> or <q>could you pass the salt?</q> You can ask it
      of <q>Since data centers demand immense power, we must expand the
      electrical grid,</q> and the answer is not obvious until you stop and
      look closely (and might not be obvious even then).
    </p>
    <p>
      This book is about how to look closely.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-language">
    <title>What We Do With Language</title>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-catalog">
      <title>A short list of things we do with language</title>
      <p>
        Take all the things people do with language — every overheard
        sentence, every text, every email — and you can sort them, loosely,
        into a handful of types. The list isn't exact; many sentences do
        more than one thing at once, and philosophers of language have
        argued for a long time about exactly how the categories work. But
        for our purposes, a working list looks something like this.
      </p>
      <dl>
        <li>
          <title>Stating</title>
          <p>
            <q>It's raining.</q> <q>The library closes at nine.</q>
            <q>Data centers consume a lot of power.</q> Statements assert
            that something is the case. They can be true or false, and that
            is the property we are going to care about most.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Asking</title>
          <p>
            <q>What time is it?</q> <q>Did you eat already?</q> Questions
            request information. They aren't true or false themselves, even
            though their answers might be.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Commanding</title>
          <p>
            <q>Close the door.</q> <q>Show your ID.</q> Commands and
            requests try to get someone to do something. They're not true or
            false either, though there are good and bad ones.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Promising</title>
          <p>
            <q>I'll be there by seven.</q> <q>We'll consider your
            application by the fifteenth.</q> A promise commits the speaker
            to some future action. It's evaluable in its own way — promises
            are kept or broken — but not as true or false at the moment of
            speaking.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Expressing</title>
          <p>
            <q>Ouch.</q> <q>What a beautiful day.</q> Expressions report or
            perform an inner state. They're sincere or insincere, fitting
            or off-key, but again, not really true or false.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Performing</title>
          <p>
            Some sentences make something happen just by being said in the
            right circumstances. <q>I now pronounce you married.</q>
            <q>I name this ship the <em>Enterprise</em>.</q>
            <q>I apologize.</q> The philosopher J. L. Austin called these
            <term>performative</term> sentences and noticed they're a
            strange beast: they don't describe a marriage, a naming, or an
            apology — they constitute one.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Greeting</title>
          <p>
            <q>Good morning.</q> <q>Hey.</q> <q>How's it going.</q> A great
            deal of human conversation is just acknowledging that other
            humans exist and are not strangers. The semantic content of
            <q>How's it going</q> is roughly zero. The social work it does
            is enormous.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Explaining</title>
          <p>
            <q>The reason your phone is hot is that you've been on it for
            two hours.</q> <q>I'm late because there was an accident on
            Route 17.</q> Explanations look a lot like arguments — they
            offer reasons connected to a claim — and we'll come back to
            that resemblance later.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Arguing</title>
          <p>
            <q>You shouldn't take Route 17 — there was an accident, and
            traffic is backed up to the next exit.</q> <q>We need to expand
            the grid because data centers are coming online faster than we
            can power them.</q> An argument offers reasons in support of a
            claim. The reasons are called <term>premises</term>, the
            supported claim is called the <term>conclusion</term>, and the
            relationship between them is mostly what the rest of this book
            is about.
          </p>
        </li>
      </dl>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-two-senses">
      <title>Two senses of <q>argument</q></title>
      <p>
        The word <term>argument</term> is ambiguous in everyday English. It
        often refers to a verbal disagreement — two people exchanging
        insults, or yelling at each other about whether the runner was
        safe: <q>He was out!</q> <q>No way! He was safe!</q> That kind of
        dispute is not what we'll mean by <em>argument</em> in this book.
        We'll be using the word in the more specialized sense from the
        catalog above: an offering of reasons in support of a claim. From
        here on, when you see <em>argument</em>, that's the meaning to
        assume.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-persuading">
      <title>Persuading and arguing</title>
      <p>
        One thing you might notice in the list above is that I haven't said
        anything about <em>persuading</em>. That's deliberate. Persuasion
        isn't really a separate category — it's something a person can be
        trying to do across many of the categories at once. Importantly,
        you can persuade someone <em>without</em> arguing.
      </p>
      <p>
        Advertising is the cleanest example. Most ads don't make arguments.
        They show you a beautiful person enjoying a beautiful product in
        beautiful light, and they hope that you, watching, will associate
        the product with the feeling of beauty. There's no premise, no
        conclusion, no reasoning offered. There's just an emotional
        pairing. If you walk away from the ad wanting the product, the ad
        has succeeded — but it did not argue.
      </p>
      <p>
        Politicians do this too. So do friends, parents, salespeople,
        professors, and AI chatbots. A great deal of persuasion happens
        through repetition, charm, fear, social pressure, identity, and
        the sheer confidence with which a claim is delivered. None of this
        is arguing. None of it requires reasons.
      </p>
      <p>
        The reverse is also true. You can make a careful, airtight argument
        and persuade exactly nobody. Anyone who has tried to talk an
        unwilling family member out of a strongly held belief knows the
        experience.
      </p>
      <p>
        Logic is about the <em>reasoning</em> embedded in argumentative
        speech, not about whether the reasoning works on its audience.
        Whether arguments persuade is mostly a question of human
        psychology, and humans are persuaded by all sorts of things that
        have nothing to do with reasons. Whether arguments are
        <em>good</em> is a different question — a logical question — and
        it is the one we will spend the rest of this book learning to
        answer.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-good-argument">
      <title>What makes an argument good?</title>
      <p>
        The central observation of the opening was that arguments are the
        kind of language use about which we can ask, <q>is this any good?</q>
        You can ask other questions of other kinds of speech: whether a
        promise was kept, whether a question was relevant, whether an
        explanation was satisfying, whether a greeting was warm. But
        <q>is this argument any good?</q> is a question that implies a
        specific structure, and the structure implied by that question is
        what the rest of the book is for.
      </p>
      <p>
        What does it actually mean for an argument to be good?
      </p>
      <p>
        A first answer: a good argument is one whose conclusion really does
        follow from its premises. If the premises support the conclusion,
        then accepting the premises gives you reason to accept the
        conclusion. If the premises do not support the conclusion, the
        argument is bad — even if every sentence in it happens to be true.
        Bad reasoning can land on a true conclusion by accident; good
        reasoning can sometimes land on a false conclusion if the premises
        were false. Both happen all the time. This is because a good
        argument isn't just about truth and falsity.
      </p>
      <p>
        Logicians have a specific vocabulary for these properties. The word
        <term>valid</term> means roughly <q>the conclusion really does
        follow from the premises,</q> and it applies to the structure of
        an argument, not its content. And the word <term>sound</term> means
        <q>valid, and the premises are also actually true.</q> For now,
        treat those as labels; we will fill in their precise meanings in
        the next chapter. The point is that those are the questions you
        can ask of an argument and not of <q>good morning.</q>
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-two-kinds">
      <title>Two kinds of arguing</title>
      <p>
        Arguments come in two broad kinds, and we'll discuss both in this
        book.
      </p>
      <p>
        Some arguments are <term>deductive</term>. In a deductive argument,
        the premises are supposed to <em>guarantee</em> the conclusion — if
        the premises are true, the conclusion has to be true too, no
        exceptions. <q>All humans are mortal. Socrates is human. Therefore
        Socrates is mortal.</q> If you accept the premises, you can't dodge
        the conclusion without contradicting yourself. Most of Parts I, II,
        and III of this book are about deductive reasoning.
      </p>
      <p>
        Other arguments are <term>inductive</term>. In an inductive
        argument, the premises don't guarantee the conclusion, but they
        make it more <em>likely</em> than it would have been otherwise.
        <q>The last hundred swans I saw were white. So the next swan I see
        will probably be white too.</q> The conclusion isn't forced; it's
        supported. Inductive arguments are the workhorses of science,
        statistics, medicine, and most everyday reasoning. Part IV of this
        book is about inductive reasoning, with statistical inference as
        its centerpiece.
      </p>
      <p>
        Both kinds count as arguing. Both can be done well or badly. The
        standards of <q>good</q> are different in each case — what makes a
        deductive argument good is not the same as what makes an inductive
        one good — but in both cases we can ask the same question we asked
        above: <em>is this argument any good?</em>
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-where-headed">
      <title>Where we're headed</title>
      <p>
        To talk about arguments precisely, we need vocabulary for their
        parts. Arguments are built out of <term>statements</term> — claims
        that are either true or false — combined in particular ways. Some
        statements serve as premises, some as conclusions, and in compound
        arguments some serve as both. Not all sentences are statements,
        though: greetings, questions, and commands aren't, as the list
        above suggests. The next section gets specific about what
        statements are and how to recognize them, because we can't say
        much about arguments without first saying what they're made of.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-1-1-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Listen for ten minutes</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find a public space — a coffee shop, a hallway between classes,
          a bus stop, a dorm common area — and listen for ten minutes
          without participating. (You can pretend to be on your phone.
          Nobody will notice.)
        </p>
        <p>
          While you listen, try to spot the different kinds of language
          use from the catalog above. You don't have to be exact, and many
          things you hear will fit more than one category at once. Notice
          especially:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              How often you hear someone making an actual argument — that
              is, giving reasons in support of a claim.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Where the arguments tend to appear (between strangers, close
              friends, parents and kids, strangers with strong opinions
              about parking).
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Whether anything you heard <em>sounded</em> like an argument
              but, on second thought, was doing a different job — an
              explanation, a complaint, a vent, a recital of grievances.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          You don't have to write any of this down right now. The point is
          just to start noticing the difference. We'll come back to it in
          an end-of-chapter writing prompt, where you'll be asked to
          report and reflect on what you heard.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>

